4.3 Semantic POD-TAMP Model Definition

We formalize our Semantic POD-TAMP system using a model taken from the work of Bonet
and Geffner [4]. The model is a tuple:

M = ⟨S, S0, SG, A, f, O⟩

where:

• S (States): A finite set of abstract states. Each state is a consistent assignment of truth
values to a set of atomic propositions AP built from K-literals (see Chapter 2). These
propositions are grounded in the Boxel representation, e.g., K(InBoxel(objk, Boxelj)).
• S0 (Initial States): The set of possible initial abstract states, representing the initial
belief b0.
• SG (Goal States): The set of goal states to be reached with certainty, specified by a logical
formula over AP (e.g., K(holding(target_obj))).
• A (Actions): A set of abstract actions defined as PDDLStream action schemas that oper
ate on the belief state, such as ‘sense_Boxel_for_object‘ or ‘pick_object_from_known_Boxel‘.
• f (Transition Function): A deterministic state-transition function s' = f(a, s) that
computes the successor abstract state based on an action’s effects on the K-literals.
• O (Sensor Model): An observation function that maps a belief state and an action to an
abstract observation (e.g., ‘found_target‘, ‘not_found_target‘), which is used to update
the belief state.

The planning problem is to find a sequence of actions from A that drives the belief state,
initially b0 = S0, to a belief state bg where all possible states are goal states (i.e., bg ⊆ SG).

