5 Evaluation Plan

To validate our proposed framework, we will conduct a series of experiments in a simulated
robotic manipulation environment.

5.1 Experimental Setup

• Environment: We will use a physics-based simulation environment, such as PyBullet,
with a multi-degree-of-freedom robotic manipulator (e.g., a Franka Emika Panda arm).
• Tasks: The primary evaluation task will be the ”hidden object” scenario, where the robot
must find and manipulate a target object occluded by other objects. This task is designed
to explicitly require strategic information-gathering actions. We will vary the number of
occluders and the complexity of the scene to test scalability.
• Perception: We will assume access to a perception system that can detect known objects
and estimate their poses from simulated sensor data. This can be implemented via a
stream that interfaces with a library like Bayes3D [11] or a mock perception oracle that
provides pose estimates with simulated uncertainty.

5.2 Evaluation Metrics

To facilitate direct comparison with state-of-the-art approaches, we plan to adopt evaluation
metrics similar to those used for TAMPURA [5]. Performance will be measured based on:

• Success Rate: The percentage of problem instances successfully solved within a given
time limit.
• Planning Time: The wall-clock time required for the planner to find a solution. This
will be a key metric for evaluating the tractability of our approach.

16

5 Evaluation Plan

• Plan Quality / Cost: The length or cost of the executed plan (e.g., number of actions,
total path length of the end-effector). This helps assess the efficiency of the generated
plans.
• Scalability: We will analyze how the above metrics change as the problem complex
ity increases (e.g., by increasing the number of objects, occluders, or the size of the
workspace).

5.3 Baselines for Comparison

The performance of our adaptive Boxel-based POD-TAMP framework will be compared against
several baselines to highlight the specific contributions of our approach:

Uniform Voxelization: A version of our planner that uses a fine-grained, uniform
voxel grid to represent spatial belief, instead of adaptive Boxels. This will directly test the
scalability benefits of our adaptive approach.

Fixed Semantic Regions: A baseline using a fixed, pre-defined set of Critical Regions
(inspired by [20]), to evaluate the advantages of our dynamic, object-centric region
generation.

POMDP-based TAMP (Conceptual/Simplified): If feasible, we will compare against
a simplified implementation or published results of a POMDP-based TAMP system like
TAMPURA [5] on a similar task. This will help contextualize the trade-offs between our
deterministic action approach and a fully probabilistic one.

The goal of this evaluation is to empirically demonstrate whether our proposed framework
offers a scalable and effective solution for TAMP under partial observability, particularly for
tasks that require reasoning about occlusions and information gathering.

5.4 conclusion

This paper presented a novel approach to Task and Motion Planning under partial observability
by integrating a semantic spatial abstraction, termed Boxels, with a Partially Observable Deter
ministic planning framework. The core of our methodology is the adaptive semantic discretiza
tion of the workspace, which provides a scalable and task-relevant representation of spatial
uncertainty. By modeling belief states over these Boxels, our system allows a PDDLStream
based TAMP framework to reason effectively about object locations and occlusions.

The proposed Semantic POD-TAMP model formalizes this integration, enabling the planner to
generate and execute plans that seamlessly combine information-gathering and manipulation
actions. The use of K-literals to represent knowledge within the PDDL state allows for a direct
and conceptually simple integration with existing POD planners. As demonstrated, this enables
the robot to reason about what it knows and where uncertainty lies, and to take actions to
resolve that uncertainty in a targeted manner.

17

5 Evaluation Plan

The expected contribution of this research is a scalable and robust framework for TAMP in
partially known environments. By moving away from exhaustive state-space representations
and leveraging a semantically meaningful abstraction, this work paves the way for more
autonomous and capable robotic systems that can operate effectively in the complexities of the
real world. Future work will focus on extending the variety of semantic information used for
discretization and exploring more complex, multi-robot planning scenarios.

